body:
@toobaz The example index [0, 1, False] is a duplicate index (0 and False are equivalent), which I described as not being covered by this PR. However, you are right that the PR does not cover the case with unique mixed-integer indices (e.g. [0, True, 2]). I will add a "self.holds_integer()" to the condition to cover this, since the function is already implemented. 

This would not cover "mixed-float" (e.g. [1.5, True]), which is 'mixed' inferred type in pandas but 'mixed' could also be ['ab', True] in which case it would be an incorrect warning. So I'll leave that one out.

Edit: I will only add a self.holds_integer() condition in case it's a warning. Since a user with [0, True, 2] index should be able to drop the True without an Error. Even if that user may drop the 0 by passing [False].
